{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565407"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:26:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:26:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17424"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.03,0.14,0.11,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70591"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10114"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2246"},{"type":"tags","id":"2286"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"9736"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23701"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70591"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three weeks of progressive shortness of breath. She has also experienced a productive cough with yellow sputum and low-grade fevers over the past week. She has a medical history of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction and chronic kidney disease. Her medications include furosemide, ramipril, bisoprolol, and spironolactone. She has gained 4 kg in weight over the past month.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe migrated from Vietnam 30 years ago and is an ex-smoker with a 40 pack-year history, having quit 15 years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly short of breath at rest. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 93% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is reduced air entry and dullness to percussion at both lung bases. She has peripheral oedema to her mid-shins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChest X-ray shows bilateral pleural effusions. Pleural fluid analysis reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProtein: 25 g/L (serum 65 g/L)\u003Cbr /\u003ELactate dehydrogenase (LDH): 140 U/L (serum 350 U/L)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 100 \u00d7 10\u2076/L\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignant pleural effusion","Chylous pleural effusion","Tuberculous pleural effusion","Parapneumonic effusion","Transudative pleural effusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with bilateral pleural effusions in the context of known heart failure with recent weight gain suggesting fluid overload. Despite her recent respiratory tract infection symptoms and significant smoking history, the pleural fluid analysis confirms a transudative effusion according to Light\u0027s criteria (pleural fluid protein/serum protein ratio \u0026lt; 0.5, and pleural fluid LDH/serum LDH ratio \u0026lt; 0.6).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransudative pleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is most commonly caused by heart failure, as in this case. Other causes include cirrhosis with hepatic hydrothorax and nephrotic syndrome. The low protein and LDH content reflects the mechanism of formation, which is due to altered hydrostatic or oncotic pressures rather than inflammation or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant pleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is typically exudative with higher protein and LDH levels. While this patient has risk factors including smoking history, the bilateral nature and transudative characteristics make this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParapneumonic effusion\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the context of pneumonia and would be exudative with elevated white cell count and LDH. Although this patient has symptoms suggesting a recent lower respiratory tract infection, the pleural fluid analysis is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculous pleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is an exudative effusion characterised by lymphocytic predominance and elevated adenosine deaminase levels. While the patient\u0027s Vietnamese background might raise concern for tuberculosis, the bilateral nature and transudative characteristics make this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChylous pleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E contains high levels of triglycerides and appears milky. It typically occurs due to disruption of the thoracic duct and would be unlikely to present bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Light\u0027s criteria distinguish transudative from exudative pleural effusions based on protein and lactate dehydrogenase ratios.","Transudative pleural effusions are most commonly caused by heart failure, cirrhosis, or nephrotic syndrome.","Bilateral pleural effusions are more likely to be transudative than exudative in nature."],"references":["Mercer RM, Corcoran JP, Porcel JM, Rahman NM, Psallidas I. Interpreting pleural fluid results\u2002. Clin Med (Lond). 2019 May;19(3):213-217. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.19-3-213. PMID: 31092513; PMCID: PMC6542220","Karkhanis VS, Joshi JM. Pleural effusion: diagnosis, treatment, and management. Open Access Emerg Med. 2012 Jun 22;4:31-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27147861/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T22:23:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-15T22:24:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10114"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70591"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of thei